"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:4.4.1\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">4.4.1</span> Pan, pot, pail</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">סִיר</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(sir)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod27:3\">EXO 27:3</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod38:3\">EXO 38:3</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Kgs7:45\">1KI 7:45</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs25:14\">2KI 25:14</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Chr4:11\">2CH 4:11</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Chr4:16\">2CH 4:16</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer52:18\">JER 52:18</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer52:19\">JER 52:19</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Zech14:20\">ZEC 14:20</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Zech14:21\">ZEC 14:21</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description and usage:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/WEB-0450_pot.jpg\" alt=\"Bronze cauldron with swinging handle (Etruscan, ca. 550 BCE)\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">Bronze cauldron with swinging handle (Etruscan, ca. 550 BCE) (Metropolitan Museum of Art, CC0, MMA)</figcaption></figure>The pot was a bronze container used to collect the ashes and animal remains that were on the altar after the sacrificial victim had been burned. The same implement could serve, in another context, as a simple, fairly large cooking pot (see <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">5.12 Cooking pot, kettle&lt;REALIA:5.12&gt;</a>).</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>See the comments at <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">4.4 Tabernacle and Temple implements&lt;REALIA:4.4&gt;</a> above.</p>\n<p>\n            <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer52:18\">JER 52:18</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer52:19\">JER 52:19</a> mentions <em>sir</em> two times as an object carried off to Babylon. It is not clear if two different items are referred to by the same name or if one item has been listed twice. Almost all translations consulted include the same word twice. <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Zech14:20\">ZEC 14:20</a>; <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Zech14:21\">ZEC 14:21</a> speaks of a time when even common things will be put to holy use. The <em>sir</em> in verse 20 is the Temple implement described here, while the <em>sir</em> in verse 21 is the everyday pot in every home in Judah, which will one day be put into service like a Temple implement.</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
